  "prompt": "If ballots were cast by contributing money, who would win the 2016 election?",
  "response": "If ballots in the 2016 U.S. presidential election were cast by contributing money, Donald Trump would likely have won, as he significantly outraised and outspent his opponent, Hillary Clinton.\n\n### Key Points:\n- **Fundraising**: According to the Center for Responsive Politics, Donald Trump raised approximately $957.6 million during the 2016 election cycle, compared to Hillary Clinton's $768.0 million.\n- **Spending**: Trump also outspent Clinton, with his campaign and supporting groups spending around $795.6 million, compared to Clinton's $770.7 million.\n- **Small Donors**: Trump had a stronger reliance on small-dollar donors, which could be interpreted as a form of \"voting\" with money from a broader base of individuals.\n\n### Caveats:\n- While Trump raised and spent more, it\u2019s important to note that fundraising does not always correlate directly with election outcomes. Clinton won the popular vote by nearly 3 million votes, even though she lost the Electoral College.\n- External spending by Super PACs and other groups also played a significant role, complicating the direct comparison of campaign funds.\n\nIn summary, if money determined the outcome, Donald Trump would have won the 2016 election based on his superior fundraising and spending numbers.",
